Power Reporting

RQ1: What is the norm when it comes to conducting and reporting statistical power analysis?

  • No mention of statistical power at all;
  • Mentioned power but no power analysis;
  • Post-hoc power analysis;
  • Sensitivity power analysis: Using the obtained sample size to estimate detectable effect size or power;
  • A priori/Prospective power analysis: Estimating the required sample size for a chosen effect size

The three figures below display the distribution of power analysis reporting for the whole sample (FigureÂ 1), by journal (FigureÂ 2), and across time (FigureÂ 3) .

Overall

Estimating the Overall Power

RQ2: How much power would the ensemble of our experimental research have to detect effect sizes that could be reasonably expected?

Our analysis is â¦.

  • limited to between-subjects designs
  • a âsensitivity power analysisâ 1:
    • not âtheâ power it had;
    • but an estimate of the general level of power for this collection of studies
      • given each studyâs sample size
      • assuming an effect size

The decision-making process

Such an analyses involves a few decisionsâ

  1. what effect sizes to assume

We consulted these existing benchmarks:

We decided to use the range of ESs as shown below, which included the empirically-derived benchmarks (SchÃ¤fer and Schwarz 2019) and the average effect size from the meta-meta-analysis of communication research (Rains, Levine, and Weber 2018), as is shown below. The empirical benchmarks were based on a random selection of 93 preregistered studies across different sub-disciplines of psychology [SchÃ¤fer and Schwarz (2019)]2.

  1. what study design to assume

In previous assessments like this, an independent-sample, 2-tailed t-test is assumed across the board (e.g., (Elson and Przybylski 2017), (Fraley and Vazire 2014), (Nuijten et al. 2020)). Such an oversimplification would gloss over the basic differences in experimental design such as the number of experimental factors, and the estimate so derived would be too crude an assessment. Our sample, as TableÂ 1 shows, had more than half of the studies with a two-way or higher-order design.

Code

For a primary study, effect size is calibrated given the experimental design and power is estimated accordingly. We therefore decide to take into consideration three basic designs as prototypical scenarios for effect size calibration and power estimation, as is shown below:

Power estimate by design

We created three subsets of data:

Code 
# data subsets for different designs:

2-group design

Code 
## Step 2a: write a function to run power analysis for a 2-group design 
## with d as an input, and using the `pwr` package

power.2cell <- function(d) {
  power.estimate <- pwr.t.test(n = data.2cell$n_cell, d = d, sig.level = 0.05,
                               type = "two.sample")  # run `pwr` power analysis
  power.results.frame <- data.frame(data.2cell$n_cell, data.2cell$jid, data.2cell$area,
                                    powerper = sprintf("%.2f%%", power.estimate$power * 100), 
                                    power = round(power.estimate$power, 2))  #store results
  return(power.results.frame$power)
}

# Step 2b: run the function to get power for different d 
d.2 <- power.2cell(0.2)
d.35 <- power.2cell(0.35)
d.43 <- power.2cell(0.43)
d.5 <- power.2cell(0.5)

# Step 2c: then create a data frame 
# and create a stacked data set with d as a variable 

df.power.2cell <- data.frame(d.2, d.35, d.43, d.5)
head(df.power.2cell)
range(df.power.2cell)

# stack up data so that d becomes a factor
data.2cell.power <- stack(df.power.2cell)
data.2cell.power <- data.2cell.power %>%
  mutate(d = recode(ind, 
                    d.2 = "d=.2", 
                    d.35 = "d=.35", 
                    d.43 = "d=.43", 
                    d.5 = "d=.5"))
data.2cell.power$power <- data.2cell.power$values

One-way multi-group design

Code 
## -- Step 3: Power analysis for one-way multi-group design -----
## Power is estimated for the omnibus one-way 

## Step 3a: write a function to run power analysis for the one-way anova omnibus test
## with f as an input, and using the `pwr` package

power.1way <- function(f) {
  power.estimate <- pwr.anova.test(k = data.1way$b_cells_adjust, 
                                   n = data.1way$n_cell,
                                   f = f, sig.level = 0.05)
  power.results.frame <- data.frame(data.1way$n_cell, data.1way$jid, data.1way$area,
                                    powerper = sprintf("%.2f%%", power.estimate$power * 100), 
                                    power = round(power.estimate$power, 2))  #store results
  return(power.results.frame$power)
}

## Step 3b: run the function to get power for different fs

Two-way factorial design (assuming 2 x 2)

Code 
data.2way <- data.2way %>%
  mutate(cellsize = round(n_adjust/4, 0))  
# n_adjust was a variable that adjusted the sample size for a fully-crossed design. 
# That is, if design is 2 x 2 + 1 control, n_adjust = n/5 * 4

summary(data.2way$cellsize)  
#cellsize: the cell size assuming 2 x 2 interaction for all studies

First of all, we reduced all factorial studies to a basic 2 x 2 design (k = 176). Cell size were recalculated as the total sample size divided by four. The median of the adjusted cell size was 52.5 (range: 6, 331). Overall, our procedure should lead to a more liberal estimate of the power for interaction effects, since power usually dissipates quickly as the design gets more complex. Â 

In FigureÂ 6, we depicted three scenarios of interaction effects, based on a baseline effect of a group difference of d = .43 (i.e., the ES for Factor 1 before Factor 2 is added to the study). F2 can interact with F1 in three ways: 1) reversal, 2) full attenuation, and 3) partial attenuation. To compute power for a 2 x 2 interaction, the effect size to be used depends on the shape of the interaction.

Code

#| label: estimating power for reversal/disordinal interaction
#| echo: true
#| results: hide
#| warning: false
#| cache: true

# Step 4a-1: write a function based on `Superpower`
power.disord <- Vectorize(function(n) {
  design_result <- ANOVA_design(design = "2b*2b", n = n, 
                                mu = c(0, 0.43, 0.43, 0), sd = 1,
                                plot = FALSE)
  power.main1 <- ANOVA_exact(design_result, 
                             verbose = FALSE)$main_results$power[1]
  power.main2 <- ANOVA_exact(design_result, 
                             verbose = FALSE)$main_results$power[2]
  power.int <- ANOVA_exact(design_result, 
                           verbose = FALSE)$main_results$power[3]
  power.pc <- ANOVA_exact(design_result, 
                          verbose = FALSE)$pc_results$power[1]
  power <- c(power.main1, power.main2, power.int, power.pc)
  return(power)
})

disord.output <- power.disord(data.2way$cellsize)

# Step 4a-2: creating a dataframe to store the results
disord.output2 <- rbind(disord.output, data.2way$cellsize, data.2way$id, 
                        data.2way$year, data.2way$area1, data.2way$journal, 
                        data.2way$b_cells_adjust, data.2way$factor)
disord.output2 <- as.data.frame(disord.output2)
row.names(disord.output2) <- c("Main1", "Main2", "Interaction", "Simple",
                               "cellsize", "id", "year", "area", "journal", 
                               "cellnum", "factornum")

data.disord.power <- disord.output2 %>%
  t() %>%
  as.data.frame()  #transpose the dataframe

  dplyr::mutate_at(c("Main1", "Main2", "Interaction", "Simple", "cellsize",
                     "id", "cellnum", "factornum"), as.numeric) %>%
  mutate(across(where(is.numeric), round, digits = 2))

  geom_point(alpha = 0.2, position = position_jitter(width = 0.1)) + 
  geom_boxplot(width = 0.4, alpha = 0.2, fill = NA, outlier.shape = NA) + 
  stat_summary(fun = "mean", geom = "point", 
               shape = 2, size = 3, color = "blue") + 
  scale_size_manual(values = c(0.5,  1), guide = "none") + 
  scale_x_discrete(labels = c("Disordinal", "Ordinal_Full", "Ordinal_Partial")) + 
  coord_flip() + 
  labs(x = "", y = "Interaction Power") +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0.8, linetype = "dashed", 
             color = "blue", linewidth = 0.8) +
  theme_bw() + theme(axis.title.y = element_blank(), 
                     axis.ticks.y = element_blank(),
                     axis.text.y = element_text(face = "bold", color = "blue", 
                                                size = 12, angle = 30))

## ridgeplot
int2 <- data.2way.power %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = int.power, y = type, fill = factor(after_stat(quantile)))) +
  stat_density_ridges(geom = "density_ridges_gradient", calc_ecdf = TRUE,
                      quantiles = 4, quantile_lines = TRUE, 
                      alpha = 0.8, scale = 0.9) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 1, 0.25), limits = c(0, 1)) + 
  scale_fill_brewer(name = "Quartiles") +
  scale_size_manual(values = c(0.5, 1), guide = "none") + 
  labs(y = "", x = "Interaction Power") +
  geom_vline(xintercept = 0.8, linetype = "dashed", 
             color = "blue", linewidth = 0.8) +
  theme_bw() + theme(legend.position = "none") + 
  theme(axis.ticks.x = element_blank()) +
  theme(legend.key.size = unit(0.8, "line")) + 
  theme(legend.title = element_text(size = 8),  
        axis.text.y = element_blank(), legend.text = element_text(size = 8))

int1 + int2 + plot_layout(ncol = 2, widths = c(2, 1))
